Q1.3: Enough space in cafe to have meals with teams.

On campus walking trails.  On campus sporting fields and courts to promote teamwork with others outside of our departmnts.  Large gym in a centralized location.  Different food options in different locations.
Q2.3: Nice landscape around campus.  More updated buildings made of glass.  Tracking and displaying green type items.
Q3.3: work/life balance.  Learning about future pipeline.  Patients.
Q4.3: Recognition for efforts.  Celebrating the wins.  Amenities and offerings to still feel like a startup company.
Q5.3: Having clear set goals and working to achieve them (both short and long term).  Clear succession planning with time to shadow and prepare for the new position ahead.,
Q6.3: Promoting and sharing these ideas, successes and failures with others in the company.  Spaces and meetings with a mixture of diverse backgrounds and departments
Q7.3: Recognition from all levels.  Celebrate the wins - big and small.
Q8.3: Taking time off without having to log into the computer / meetings.

Q1.3: Work hours and ability to also work flexibly/remotely
Q2.3: People's adherence to open plan etiquette and use of common spaces

Q1.3: spaces where people can do their *best* work - knowing that sometimes that work is collaborative and sometimes quiet space for deep work is needed. and those spaces need to be ergonomic, attractive and pleasant to be in, of course. having a layout that encourages physical movement is also great - meaning that not every office will have every amenity within 20 feet - having to take the stairs to get to a conference room is not a bad thing.
Q2.3: Managing noise is huge. Strategically running HVAC to provide white noise in an open office setting actually enables conversation and reduces distraction in the work spaces.
Q3.3: i am bought in to the overall purpose of Moderna, 100%. my day-to-day is very bogged down with garbage admin work related to our lack of coherent systems and antiquated digital integration. it makes my daily work much harder AND less effective relative to the effort i'm expending, so my connection to the larger purpose starts to feel more distant. systems that work MATTER for fostering a sense of purpose.
Q4.3: we talk a big game about our culture - and i believe that leaders really mean what they say. but the pace at which we are running means that we can't actually do the right things to support the culture we say we want. and the longer there is a gap between what leaders say and what we actually do - the credibility risk only grows. like seriously stop about AI and Digital - our systems are what any old-school fortune 500 company had 15 years ago. we aren't doing ANYTHING cool in 90% of the org - in fact, most of us struggle because the systems (or the 'experts' behind) are sub-par.
Q5.3: access to leaders who walk the talk. access to information about how decisions get made and what success looks like.
Q6.3: ability to network with like-minded colleagues. now, unless you know someone, networking spontaneously is nearly impossible.
Q8.3: acknowledgement that it's okay not to be perfect/"on" 100% of the time. again, lots of talking the talk, not so much walking the walk.
